The event is fired from the DefaultProjectManager, which is wrapped by the CachingProjectManager. When the ProjectCreatedEvent is fired, the CachingProjectManager doesn't know about the new project yet. Likewise for ProjectDeletedEvent.

e.g.
{code}
@EventListener
public void onProjectCreated(final ProjectCreatedEvent event)
{
    // project is null!
    Project project = projectManager.getProjectObj(event.getId());
}
{code}

Since we know that the ProjectManager is always going to be the CachingProjectManager implementation, we should just fire the events from there.

